Appeals against variation or revocation of authorisation
	The governing body of a provider may appeal to the First-tier Tribunalagainst either or both of the following—
		a decision of the OfS to vary or revoke, by a further order under section42(1) or an order under section 45(1), an authorisation given to it;
		a decision of the OfS as to the date specified under section 48(6) as thedate on which the variation or revocation takes effect.
	On an appeal under subsection (1)(a) against a decision to revoke anauthorisation, the Tribunal—
		must consider afresh the decision appealed against, and
		may take into account evidence that was not available to the OfS.
	An appeal under subsection (1), other than an appeal against a decision torevoke an authorisation, may be on the grounds—
		that the decision was based on an error in fact;
		that the decision was wrong in law;
		that the decision was unreasonable.
	On an appeal under subsection (1), the Tribunal may—
		withdraw the decision;
		confirm the decision;
		vary the date on which the variation or revocation takes effect under theorder to be made under section 42(1) or 45(1);
		remit the decision whether to confirm the decision, or any matter relatingto that decision (including the date on which the variation or revocationtakes effect), to the OfS.
	In the case of an appeal under subsection (1)(a) against a decision torevoke an authorisation, the Tribunal also has power to substitute for thedecision any other decision that the OfS could have made.
	An appeal under subsection (1)(a) against a decision to revoke anauthorisation may include an appeal against the decision mentioned insubsection (1)(b) regarding the date when the revocation takes effect; and inthe case of such an appeal, references in subsections (2), (4) and (5) to thedecision appealed against are to be read accordingly.

Funding of the OfS
	Registration fees
		The OfS may, in accordance with regulations made by the Secretary of State,charge an institution either or both of the following—
			a fee for its initial registration in the register;
			a fee for its ongoing registration in the register for each period oftwelve months.
		The regulations may, in particular, make provision—
			about the amounts which may be charged, including different amounts fordifferent institutions;
			about the charging of proportions of those amounts in certaincircumstances;
			about when a fee is payable, including about payment by instalments;
			about the consequences of non-payment;
			about notification of institutions of the fees payable, when they arepayable and the consequences of non-payment;
			about the recovery of fees and of costs in recovering those fees;
			about the imposition of financial penalties for late payment of fees;
			about rights of appeal in respect of the imposition of such penalties;
			about the charging of interest;
			about the waiving or refunding of fees.
		The regulations may provide for the amounts of fees to be calculated byreference to costs incurred, or to be incurred, by the OfS in the performanceof any of its functions (including costs unconnected with maintaining theregister or with the institution in question).
		Regulations under this section may be made only with the consent of theTreasury.
	Other fees
		The OfS may, in accordance with regulations made by the Secretary of State,charge a fee for—
			any activity undertaken by the OfS in the performance of its functionswhich is specified in the regulations;
			any service provided by it in the performance of its functions which isspecified in the regulations.
		The regulations may, in particular, make provision—
			about the persons required to pay the fees (“payees”);
			about the amounts which may be charged, including different amounts fordifferent payees;
			about the charging of proportions of those amounts in certaincircumstances;
			about when a fee is payable, including about payment by instalments;
			about the consequences of non-payment;
			about notification of payees of the fees payable, when they are payable andthe consequences of non-payment;
			about the recovery of fees and of costs in recovering those fees;
			about the imposition of financial penalties for late payment of fees;
			about rights of appeal in respect of the imposition of such penalties;
			about the charging of interest;
			about the waiving or refunding of fees.
		The regulations may provide for the amounts of fees to be calculated byreference to costs incurred by the OfS in the performance of the activity orservice in question in relation to a person other than the payee.
		If costs incurred by the OfS are costs by reference to which fees undersection 70 are calculated as a result of regulations made under that section,fees calculated by reference to those costs may not be charged under thissection.
		Regulations under this section may be made only with the consent of theTreasury.
	Retention of fee related income
		The OfS must pay its fee income to the Secretary of State except to theextent that the Secretary of State, with the consent of the Treasury, directsotherwise.
		“Fee income” means the sums received by the OfS by way of—
			fees charged under section 70 (registration fees) or 71 (other fees), or
			costs recovered by virtue of regulations made under section 70(2)(f) or71(2)(g).
		The OfS must pay its other fee related income to the Secretary of State.
		“Other fee related income” means the sums received by the OfS by way of—
			penalties imposed by virtue of regulations made under section 70(2)(g) or71(2)(h), or
			interest charged by virtue of regulations made under section 70(2)(i) or71(2)(j).
	Costs recovery
		The OfS may, by notice, require the governing body of a provider inrelation to which a sanction has been imposed to pay the costs incurred by theOfS in relation to imposing the sanction up to the date of notification.
		The references in subsection (1) to imposing a sanction are to—
			imposing a monetary penalty under section 15;
			suspending a provider’s registration under section 16;
			removing a provider from the register under section 18.
		“Costs” includes, in particular, investigation costs, administration costsand costs of obtaining expert advice (including legal advice).
		“The date of notification” means the date on which the OfS notified theprovider of its decision—
			in the case of a monetary penalty, under paragraph 2(5) of Schedule 3;
			in the case of suspension, under section 17(5);
			in the case of removal, under section 19(5).
		Schedule 7 contains provision about—
			the procedure for imposing a requirement to pay costs,
			rights of appeal,
			the recovery of the amount required to be paid and interest, and
			the retention of sums received.
	Grants from the Secretary of State
		The Secretary of State may make grants to the OfS of such amounts, andsubject to such terms and conditions, as the Secretary of State considersappropriate.
		The terms and conditions under subsection (1) may, in particular, be framedby reference to particular courses of study.
		But in determining the terms and conditions under subsection (1), theSecretary of State must have regard to the need to protect the institutionalautonomy of English higher education providers.
		The terms and conditions under subsection (1) must not relate to—
			particular parts of courses of study,
			the content of such courses,
			the manner in which they are taught, supervised or assessed,
			the criteria for the selection, appointment or dismissal of academic staff,or how they are applied, or
			the criteria for the admission of students, or how they are applied.
		Terms and conditions under subsection (1) framed by reference to aparticular course of study must not require the OfS to perform a function in away which prohibits or requires the provision of a particular course of study.
		Terms and conditions under subsection (1) relating to the provision offinancial support by the OfS under section 39 or 40 (financial support forproviders) may be imposed only if—
			they are requirements to be met before financial support of a specifiedamount or of a specified description is given by the OfS in respect ofactivities carried on by an institution, and
			they apply to every institution, or every institution within a specifieddescription, in respect of whose activities that support may be provided.
		The terms and conditions under subsection (1) may, in particular—
			enable the Secretary of State to require the repayment, in whole or inpart, of sums paid by the Secretary of State if any of the terms andconditions subject to which the sums were paid is not complied with, and
			require the payment of interest in respect of any period during which a sumdue to the Secretary of State in accordance with any of the terms andconditions remains unpaid.
		In this section “specified” means specified in the terms and conditions.

Interpretation
	Meaning of “English higher education provider” etc
		In this Part—
			  * “English higher education provider” means a higher education provider whose activities are carried on, or principally carried on, in England; 
			  * “higher education provider” means an institution which provides higher education; 
			  * “institution” includes any training provider (whether or not the training provider would otherwise be regarded as an institution); 
			  * “higher education” means education provided by means of a higher education course; 
			  * “higher education course” means a course of any description mentioned in Schedule 6 to the Education Reform Act 1988; 
			  * “training provider” means a person who provides training for members of the school workforce within the meaning of Part 3 of the Education Act 2005 (see section 100 of that Act). 
		In this Part—
			“English further education provider” means an institution in England withinthe further education sector, and
			references to an institution within the further education sector have thesame meaning as in the Further and Higher Education Act 1992 (see section91(3) of that Act).
		In this Part references to a higher education course provided in Englandare to a higher education course which is provided wholly, or principally, inEngland.
		In this Part references to an institution in a part of the United Kingdomare to an institution whose activities are carried on, or principally carriedon, in that part.
		Subsection (1) is subject to express provision to the contrary, see—
			section 10(9) (mandatory fee limit condition for certain providers),
			section 25(4) (rating the quality of, and the standards applied to, highereducation),
			section 32(5)(b) (content of an access and participation plan: equality ofopportunity), and
			section 38(5) and (6) (duty to monitor etc the provision of arrangementsfor student transfers).
	Designation of other providers of higher education
		The Secretary of State may, on the application of a provider of highereducation within subsection (2), designate the provider for the purposes ofthis section.
		A provider of higher education is within this subsection if—
			it provides higher education,
			its activities are carried on, or principally carried on, in England, and
			but for the designation it would not be regarded as an institution for thepurposes of this Part.
		A provider of higher education designated under this section is, unless thedesignation is withdrawn, to be treated for the purposes of any provision madeby or under this Part as being an institution.
		The Secretary of State may, by regulations, make provision about—
			the making of applications for designation;
			the making of designations under this section (including provision aboutmatters to be taken into account in determining whether to make adesignation);
			the withdrawal of a designation (including provision about matters to betaken into account in determining whether to withdraw a designation);
			the effect of a withdrawal of a designation (including provision for aprovider whose designation is withdrawn to continue to be treated as aninstitution for purposes prescribed in the regulations).
		Subsection (3) is subject to any provision made under subsection (4)(d).
	Other definitions
		In this Part—
			  * “an access and participation plan condition” has the meaning given by section 12(3); 
			  * “a fee limit condition” has the meaning given by section 10(2); 
			  * “foundation degree” has the meaning given by section 42(3); 
			  * “foundation degree only authorisation” has the meaning given by section 42(3); 
			  * “governing body”— 
			in relation to a training provider who, but for the definition of“institution” in section 83(1), would not be regarded as an institution, meansany persons responsible for the provider’s management;
			in relation to a provider designated under section 84 means any personsresponsible for the provider’s management;
			in relation to any other institution, has the meaning given by section 90(1)of the Further and Higher Education Act 1992, but subject to any provisionmade by virtue of section 90(2) of that Act;
				  * “the institutional autonomy of English higher education providers” has the meaning given by section 2(8); 
				  * “the register” has the meaning given by section 3(1); 
				  * “registered higher education provider” has the meaning given by section 3(10); 
				  * “registration” has the meaning given by section 3(10); 
				  * “research award” has the meaning given by section 42(3); 
				  * “sector-recognised standards” has the meaning given by section 13(3); 
				  * “taught award” has the meaning given by section 42(3). 
		In this Part, “fees” in relation to undertaking a course, means fees inrespect of, or otherwise in connection with, undertaking the course, includingadmission, registration, tuition and graduation fees and fees payable forawarding or accrediting a qualification in respect of the course, butexcluding—
			fees payable for board or lodging,
			fees payable for field trips (including any tuition element of such fees),
			fees payable for attending any graduation or other ceremony, and
			such other fees as may be prescribed by regulations made by the Secretaryof State.
		References in this Part to the ongoing registration conditions of aprovider have the meaning given by section 3(8).
		For the purposes of this Part an appeal is “pending” during the period—
			beginning when it is instituted, and
			ending when it is determined, withdrawn or abandoned.
		When construing references in this Part to a time when an appeal could bebrought, any possibility of an appeal out of time is to be ignored.

Interpretation
	Definitions 
		In this Part—
			  * “Council” has the meaning given by section 92; 
			  * “humanities” includes the arts; 
			  * “knowledge exchange” has the meaning given by section 93; 
			  * “research and innovation strategy” has the meaning given by section 99; 
			  * “science” includes social sciences. 
		In this Part, a reference to the United Kingdom includes a reference to anypart of the United Kingdom.
